      <div class="mtr">
       <div columnalign="right" class="mtd">
        <div class="mrow">
         <div class="msub">
          <span class="mi">C</span>
          <span class="mi">k</span>
         </div>
         <span mathvariant="normal" class="mi">d</span>
         <span class="mi">t</span>
         <span class="mo">=</span>
         <div class="msub">
          <span class="mi">c</span>
          <span class="mi">k</span>
         </div>
         <div class="msub">
          <span class="mi">E</span>
          <span class="mi">k</span>
         </div>
         <span mathvariant="normal" class="mi">d</span>
         <span class="mi">t</span>
         <span class="mo">,</span>
        </div>
       </div>
      </div>
     </div>
    </div>
   </div>
   <span class="label">(10)</span>
  </div> where 
  <span class="italic">C</span>
  <sub>
   <span class="italic">k</span>
  </sub> is the cost ($ m
  <span class="sup">−2</span> s
  <span class="sup">−1</span>) associated with the effort exerted on fishing group 
  <span class="italic">k</span>, and 
  <span class="italic">c</span>
  <sub>
   <span class="italic">k</span>
  </sub> ($ W
  <span class="sup">−1</span> s
  <span class="sup">−1</span>) is the cost per unit effort. We estimate the global cost per unit effort forcing by assuming that the real world was close to an open-access equilibrium between 1990 and 2006, so that total global revenue was equal to the total global cost, which is a reasonable first-order assumption based on the fishing cost database of Lam et al., [
  <a rid="pone.0169763.ref055" ref-type="bibr" href="#pone.0169763.ref055">55</a>] (see Table 5 of that article). Thus, we divide the global revenue from the SAUP harvest database by the global effort as reported in [
  <a rid="pone.0169763.ref001" ref-type="bibr" href="#pone.0169763.ref001">1</a>]. We presently assume that cost has no spatial dependence, for simplicity. Although this ignores the potentially-important role of the transit distance between fishing grounds and ports, it avoids a great deal of complexity, and could be revisited in future work.
 </p>
